Packaging, layers, and configuration.

You ship code into Lambda in three ways, by size. An inline zip in the console, up to three megabytes of source, for tiny utility functions. A zip uploaded via S3, up to two hundred fifty megabytes unzipped, which is the standard path. Or a container image, in O-C-I format, up to ten gigabytes, for large dependencies, M-L models, or custom runtimes. Lambda Layers are versioned zip archives of shared libraries or custom runtimes that mount into the execution environment. You can use up to five layers per function, and they're shared across functions and accounts, so you keep your function packages small and avoid re-uploading large dependencies on every deploy.

Configuration is a handful of knobs. Memory runs from one hundred twenty-eight megabytes to ten thousand two hundred forty megabytes, and C-P-U scales with it, giving one full v-C-P-U at around seventeen hundred sixty-nine megabytes. Timeout runs from one second to fifteen minutes; it's a hard cap that kills the function if exceeded. The ephemeral slash-tmp directory runs from five hundred twelve megabytes to ten gigabytes and survives across warm invocations. Environment variables cap at four kilobytes and are encrypted at rest with K-M-S. And account concurrency defaults to one thousand per region, which is a soft limit.

The single most important sizing knob is the memory-to-C-P-U link. There is no direct C-P-U dial, so for C-P-U-bound work, you raise the memory until you have enough v-C-P-U, even if you don't need the extra R-A-M. Sizing memory is really sizing C-P-U.
